                '7.0' => [
                    "There's one occasion that really stands out in my memory, and it involves Mr. Tanaka, my English teacher throughout high school, who was without question a formative influence on how I approach learning in general. What really stood out was the way he made even the driest grammar points feel intellectually stimulating, often by tying them to anecdotes from his own years abroad. I had never expected that a language class could feel so engaging until I sat in his lessons, and it goes without saying that his unwavering support during my final exam year made an enormous difference to my confidence. Looking back, what strikes me most is not the grammar or vocabulary he taught, but the way he instilled in us a genuine curiosity about how language actually works, rather than a fear of getting it wrong. I still remember one lesson where he asked us to debate a topic entirely in English with no preparation, and although it was intimidating at the time, it turned out to be something of a transformative experience for my fluency. This experience has stayed with me ever since, and whenever I doubt my own ability to improve, I think back to how far his patient, unwavering support once took me.",
                    "There's one subject that really stands out for me when I think about future study, and that's psychology. I find the idea of exploring human behaviour genuinely intellectually stimulating, and what really stood out to me, after reading a handful of academic papers on resilience and motivation, was just how much a formative influence early experiences can have on adult behaviour. I had never expected a subject to change the way I see everyday interactions until I started reading about it seriously. I suspect that studying it formally would be something of a transformative experience, not only academically but personally, since it would instil in me a much more analytical way of thinking about my own decisions. It goes without saying that I would need a fair amount of unwavering support from tutors or mentors along the way, given how demanding a proper academic grounding in the subject can be. Looking back, what strikes me most is that this interest began almost by accident, through a single documentary, and yet it has stayed with me ever since, gradually convincing me that psychology is a subject I genuinely want to pursue.",
                    "There's one book that really stands out in my memory: 'Sapiens' by Yuval Noah Harari. It offered an intellectually stimulating account of human history that reframed concepts I had always taken for granted, from the origins of money to the nature of religion. I had never expected a single book to have such a formative influence on how I interpret current events, yet by the final chapter, I found myself questioning assumptions I'd held since childhood. What really stood out was the way Harari wove enormous historical arguments into a narrative that felt almost conversational, never losing its intellectual weight in the process. Reading it was, in many ways, a transformative experience, and it instilled in me a lasting habit of questioning ideas I once considered self-evident. It goes without saying that not every argument in the book has aged perfectly, but that hardly diminishes how thought-provoking the overall experience was. This experience has stayed with me ever since, and I still find myself returning to some of its ideas whenever I read the news.",
                    "There's one skill that really stands out in my memory as being difficult to master: touch-typing without glancing at the keyboard. The early stages were thoroughly demoralising, since my fingers seemed to have a mind of their own, and I had never expected something so ordinary to feel so intellectually and physically frustrating at once. What really stood out, though, was how gradual the improvement was — I barely noticed it happening until, almost overnight, it became second nature. Persevering through that period was, in many ways, a transformative experience, and it instilled in me a much deeper appreciation for the value of consistent, patient practice over dramatic, short-term effort. It goes without saying that I owed a great deal to the unwavering support of a friend who kept nudging me to practise even on days I wanted to quit entirely. This experience has stayed with me ever since, and whenever I take on something new and difficult now, I remind myself how unlikely progress felt at the very beginning of that particular struggle.",
                    "There's one occasion that really stands out in my memory: helping my younger cousin get to grips with algebra, a subject she found genuinely daunting from the very first lesson. Rather than simply repeating her textbook, I tried to make the process intellectually stimulating by drawing on everyday examples, from splitting a restaurant bill to working out discounts while shopping. What really stood out was how her attitude shifted, almost overnight, from dread to something closer to curiosity, once she realised mistakes were simply part of learning rather than something to fear. In many ways, it was a transformative experience for her, and it instilled a confidence in her that has stayed with me ever since, particularly given how unwavering her support of her own progress became once she started believing in it herself. It goes without saying that I learned a great deal too, since explaining something clearly to someone else demands a far more formative understanding of the subject than simply knowing it for yourself. This experience has stayed with me, and it occasionally makes me wonder whether teaching might be a more intellectually stimulating career path than I'd previously assumed.",
