        'environment' => [
            'questions' => [
                "Describe an environmental problem in your area.\nYou should say: what the problem is, what causes it, how it affects people, and explain what could be done about it.",
                "Describe something you do to protect the environment.\nYou should say: what you do, how often you do it, why you started doing it, and explain how it helps.",
                "Describe a natural place you have visited.\nYou should say: where it was, when you went there, what you did there, and explain why it left an impression on you.",
                "Describe an environmental change you have noticed.\nYou should say: what the change is, when you first noticed it, what caused it, and explain how you feel about it.",
                "Describe a way people can save energy at home.\nYou should say: what the method is, how it works, how effective it is, and explain why more people should do it.",
            ],
            'answers' => [
                '5.5' => [
                    "I'd like to talk about air pollution near my city. The air isn't very clean because of heavy traffic and factories close to where I live. This problem affects people because it can make breathing difficult, especially for older people and children, and it stops us from enjoying the outdoors as much as we should. It's a clear problem, especially compared to a quiet forest or park just outside the city, where the air always feels much cleaner and more beautiful. I think the government could do more by encouraging people to use buses and trains instead of cars. This is something I notice every day, and I hope it slowly starts to improve.",
                    "I'd like to talk about carrying a reusable water bottle instead of buying plastic ones. It's a small thing, but I do it every single day, whether I'm going to school or just out with friends. I started doing this after seeing pictures of plastic rubbish in the ocean, which made me feel like I wanted to help even a little. It helps by keeping places clean, like parks, beaches, and forests, since less plastic ends up as rubbish there. This is something I remember deciding quite suddenly, and now it just feels like a normal, easy habit rather than something difficult to keep up.",
                    "I'd like to talk about a national park I visited with my family, which had a large forest and a beautiful waterfall. We went there two summers ago, during the school holidays. While we were there, we walked along quiet paths through the forest and had a picnic near the waterfall, where the air felt really clean and fresh. It left an impression on me because everything felt so beautiful and quiet compared to the busy city I usually live in. This is something I remember well, especially the sound of the water and how peaceful the whole park felt that day.",
                    "I'd like to talk about hotter summers in my city, which didn't used to be like this when I was younger. I first noticed it a few years ago, when summer started feeling much longer and less comfortable than before. I think it's caused by climate change, along with more traffic and buildings in the city, which used to have more parks and open, quiet space. It's not as clean or comfortable outside any more, even in a quiet park nearby. This is something I've noticed since I was young, and honestly, it makes me feel a little worried about the future.",
                    "I'd like to talk about turning off lights and unplugging devices when they're not being used. It's an easy method that works because devices still use a small amount of electricity even on standby. It's quite effective, especially if everyone in a house does it, since the little amounts of saved energy add up over time. I think more people should do this because it's such a quick, easy way to help the environment without spending any money. It also helps keep bills lower, which is another useful reason to remember. This is something everyone can do, and I think it should become a normal, everyday habit.",
                ],
                '6.0' => [
                    "This is something I notice often — air pollution in my city, caused mainly by heavy traffic and nearby factories. First, I became aware of it during summer, when the air felt noticeably worse and less peaceful than usual. Then, I started comparing it to a park near my grandparents' house, where the fresh air and quiet scenery felt completely different. After that, I realised how much this pollution probably affects people's health, especially those with breathing problems. In the end, I think it discourages people from spending relaxing time outdoors, even in areas with a bit of wildlife nearby. Looking back now, I think the government should do more to improve air quality, perhaps by investing in cleaner public transport.",
                    "This is something I do regularly — carrying a reusable bottle and bags wherever I go. First, I started this habit after watching a documentary about plastic waste in the ocean, which honestly shocked me. Then, I began noticing how much unnecessary plastic I used to buy without even thinking about it. After that, I made it a habit to always bring my own bottle and bags, even if it meant remembering them before leaving the house. In the end, it has become such a normal part of my routine that it barely feels like effort any more. Looking back now, I think it helps in a small way by reducing waste and keeping places like parks and beaches more peaceful and clean.",
                    "This was a memorable experience because I visited a national park with a beautiful waterfall a couple of summers ago. First, we arrived early in the morning, when the park felt especially peaceful and quiet. Then, we walked for a few hours along forest trails, noticing quite a lot of wildlife along the way, including some birds I had never seen before. After that, we had a relaxing picnic near the waterfall, enjoying the fresh air and impressive scenery around us. In the end, it turned out to be one of the most relaxing days I'd had in a long time. Looking back now, the fresh air and peaceful scenery made it feel completely different from anywhere I usually spend my time.",
                    "This is something I've noticed clearly — summers becoming much hotter than they used to be. First, I remember summers as a child feeling relaxing, with cooler evenings and more time spent playing outside. Then, over the past few years, I noticed the heat lasting longer, making it harder to enjoy peaceful time outdoors, even somewhere with fresh air and a bit of wildlife nearby. After that, I started paying more attention to news about climate change, which seems to be the main cause. In the end, I think this change has made summer feel less like a relaxing season and more like something to simply get through. Looking back now, I think climate change is clearly affecting daily life, not just distant places.",
                    "This is something I try to do regularly — turning off devices completely instead of leaving them on standby. First, I learned that standby power actually uses more electricity than people realise, which surprised me quite a lot. Then, I started unplugging chargers and switching off the socket at the wall, rather than just pressing a remote's power button. After that, I noticed our electricity bill was slightly lower than before, which felt like a small, relaxing reward for such an easy change. In the end, I think it's a genuinely efficient habit that costs nothing but a little bit of extra attention. Looking back now, I think more people should try this small, peaceful change, since it barely affects daily life at all.",
                ],
                '6.5' => [
                    "It's something that leaves a lasting impression on me whenever I compare my city to the unspoiled countryside nearby — the air pollution here is a real problem, largely caused by traffic and nearby factories. What I remember most vividly is visiting a tranquil village an hour away, where the scenery felt genuinely breathtaking compared to the greyish air back home. In hindsight, spending time somewhere more tranquil really highlights how serious the issue has become, since I hadn't noticed quite how used to it I'd become until I experienced the contrast. What affects people most, I think, is not always obvious pollution, but the slow effect on health that builds up over years of breathing the same unclean air. What could genuinely help, in my opinion, is stricter regulation on factories combined with more picturesque green spaces within the city itself, rather than only at its edges. Looking back, I realise how easy it is to overlook a problem you live with every day.",
                    "It left a lasting impression on me, watching a documentary about ocean plastic, which is why I now consistently carry reusable bags and a bottle wherever I go. In hindsight, it's a small habit, but it feels meaningful whenever I picture unspoiled, tranquil places being protected from waste that might otherwise end up there. What I remember most vividly is the moment in the documentary when a turtle was shown tangled in plastic, an image that genuinely changed how I thought about my own daily habits. What made the habit easy to keep was starting small, just the bottle at first, before gradually adding reusable bags and avoiding unnecessary packaging where possible. Looking back, I realise this single change has quietly reduced how much waste I personally contribute, even if the overall impact is modest compared to what breathtaking, large-scale policy change could achieve. It's not a perfect solution, but it's one small way I try to protect the tranquil places I hope to keep visiting.",
                    "It left a lasting impression on me — a national park with a breathtaking waterfall and unspoiled forest trails, which I visited with my family two summers ago. What I remember most vividly is arriving early, when the whole area still felt genuinely tranquil, almost untouched by other visitors. We spent the day walking through picturesque trails, occasionally spotting wildlife, before settling down for a relaxing picnic within sight of the waterfall itself. In hindsight, the picturesque scenery made me appreciate nature much more than before, particularly the tranquil sound of the water compared to constant city noise. What made it particularly memorable was how completely different the pace of the day felt, unspoiled by phones, traffic, or any real schedule. Looking back, I think that sense of calm is exactly why the memory of that awe-inspiring waterfall has stayed so vividly with me since.",
                    "It's a change that leaves a lasting impression on me every year — summers becoming noticeably hotter and longer than they were during my childhood. What used to be a tranquil season, spent mostly outdoors in parks with fresh air, now feels genuinely uncomfortable for large parts of the day. I first noticed the shift several years ago, when evenings that used to feel cooler and unspoiled by heat started staying warm well into the night. In hindsight, this shift has made me take climate change far more seriously than I used to, since it no longer feels like a distant, abstract issue. What made the change particularly striking was realising how differently my parents describe their own childhood summers, which sound almost breathtaking in comparison to how uncomfortable the season feels now. Looking back, I think this gradual, easily overlooked change is precisely what makes climate change so difficult for people to take seriously until it becomes undeniable.",
                    "It's something that could leave a lasting impression on household energy use — switching devices off at the socket instead of leaving them on standby overnight. In hindsight, it's a remarkably simple habit, yet its impact, when adopted consistently across a whole household, is far from insignificant. What I remember most vividly is checking our electricity bill after a few months and noticing a genuinely noticeable difference, which convinced me the habit was worth keeping. What makes it particularly effective is how little it demands of anyone — no unspoiled countryside retreat or breathtaking lifestyle change required, just a small, tranquil moment each night switching things off properly. I think more people should adopt it precisely because it requires almost no effort or cost, unlike some picturesque but expensive solutions like solar panels. Looking back, I'd say small, consistent habits like this one are often underestimated compared with larger, more visible environmental gestures.",
                ],
                '7.0' => [
                    "There's one environmental problem that really stands out where I live: persistent air pollution driven by heavy traffic and industrial activity on the edge of the city. Visiting somewhere closer to pristine wilderness, on a recent trip, really threw this into sharp relief, since the sheer clarity of the air there felt almost profoundly moving by comparison. I had never expected something as invisible as air quality to affect me so directly until I noticed how much more restorative simply breathing felt during that trip. What really stood out was returning home and immediately sensing the difference, something I had apparently stopped registering after years of living with it. This experience has stayed with me, reinforcing how urgently cities need cleaner transport policies and genuinely enforced emissions regulations rather than vague, long-term promises. It goes without saying that no single visit to an idyllic, unpolluted place can solve a structural problem like this, but it did leave me far more conscious of how normalised the issue had become in my daily life.",
                    "There's one habit that really stands out in how I try to help the environment: consistently avoiding single-use plastic in favour of reusable bottles and bags. This experience has stayed with me since watching a documentary that vividly captured how pristine wilderness and marine life are affected by waste that most of us barely think about once it leaves our hands. It's a modest effort, but one I find genuinely restorative to maintain, partly because it gives me a small sense of agency over an otherwise overwhelming global problem. What really stood out, watching that documentary, was an awe-inspiring vista of open ocean gradually revealed to be full of near-invisible plastic fragments, an image I had never expected to find so profoundly moving. I had never seriously considered my own contribution to that kind of damage until that moment. This experience instilled in me a fairly disciplined habit that I've maintained ever since, and although I recognise that individual action alone won't restore an idyllic, unpolluted ocean, it feels like the least I can do while larger, systemic changes hopefully follow.",
                    "There's one place that really stands out in my memory: a national park featuring an awe-inspiring vista over dense, pristine wilderness, which I visited with my family a couple of summers ago. Standing near the waterfall was, in a quiet way, profoundly moving, largely because the sheer scale of it made everything back home feel remarkably small by comparison. We spent the day walking through what felt like genuinely idyllic, untouched trails, occasionally pausing simply to take in scenery I had never expected to find so restorative. What really stood out was how little effort it took to feel completely at peace there, something I hadn't realised I was missing until that particular afternoon. This experience has stayed with me, and it deepened my appreciation for protecting such idyllic natural spaces, especially compared with how quickly similar wilderness elsewhere seems to be disappearing. It goes without saying that no photograph could ever fully capture how genuinely awe-inspiring the whole vista felt in person.",
                    "There's one change that really stands out to me: the way summers have grown markedly hotter compared to my childhood, when the season felt like an idyllic, restorative break rather than something to endure. Somewhere that once felt like an escape into fresh air and unspoiled scenery now feels considerably less restorative during peak heat, to the point where spending an afternoon outdoors can feel genuinely draining rather than enjoyable. I first noticed this shift gradually, without any single profoundly moving moment, which is precisely what makes it unsettling in hindsight. This experience has stayed with me as a personal, tangible reminder of climate change, distinct from the more abstract awe-inspiring statistics we tend to hear in the news. What really stood out, comparing notes with my parents, was how their memories of summer sound almost unrecognisable next to my own. It goes without saying that no single hot summer proves anything on its own, but the cumulative, creeping pattern over the years has genuinely changed how seriously I take the issue.",
                    "There's one habit that really stands out as an easy way to save energy at home: switching devices off completely rather than leaving them on standby around the clock. This experience has stayed with me since I first noticed the difference in my electricity bill, and it strikes me as a modest but genuinely worthwhile change for most households to adopt. What really stood out, once I researched it further, was how much cumulative energy standby devices quietly consume across an entire country, an almost profoundly moving statistic once you consider it at that scale. I had never expected something so mundane to feel like a small, personal contribution to something as vast as national energy consumption. It goes without saying that this single habit won't restore any pristine wilderness on its own, but it requires no idyllic lifestyle change, no expensive technology, and no real sacrifice, which is precisely why I think more people should adopt it. This experience instilled in me a habit I now barely think about, yet its restorative effect on both my bills and, in a small way, the environment, feels genuinely worth maintaining.",
                ],
            ],
        ],
    ],

